## 3.5 GROUPING SETS, ROLLUP, CUBE

🧠 *"I need subtotals and grand totals without running separate queries."*

**Which to reach for:**

| You want… | Use |
|---|---|
| Hierarchical subtotals — "by region, by region+product, plus a grand total" | `ROLLUP(region, product)` |
| Every possible combination — "by region, by product, by both, and grand total" | `CUBE(region, product)` |
| A specific set of groupings you hand-pick (not a fixed hierarchy) | `GROUPING SETS (…)` |

In other words: `ROLLUP` is `CUBE` restricted to a prefix hierarchy; `GROUPING SETS` is the escape hatch for everything else.

```sql
-- ROLLUP: hierarchical subtotals (rightmost to leftmost)
SELECT region, product, SUM(sales) AS total
FROM sales_data
GROUP BY ROLLUP(region, product);
-- Produces: (region, product), (region, NULL), (NULL, NULL) ← grand total

-- CUBE: all possible combinations
SELECT region, product, SUM(sales) AS total
FROM sales_data
GROUP BY CUBE(region, product);
-- Produces: (region, product), (region, NULL), (NULL, product), (NULL, NULL)

-- GROUPING SETS: specify exact combinations
SELECT region, product, SUM(sales) AS total
FROM sales_data
GROUP BY GROUPING SETS (
    (region, product),   -- detail
    (region),            -- subtotal by region
    ()                   -- grand total
);
```

### Distinguishing NULLs from Subtotals

The `GROUPING()` function returns 1 when the NULL is from a subtotal, 0 when it's a real NULL in data:

```sql
SELECT
    CASE WHEN GROUPING(region) = 1 THEN 'ALL REGIONS' ELSE region END AS region,
    CASE WHEN GROUPING(product) = 1 THEN 'ALL PRODUCTS' ELSE product END AS product,
    SUM(sales) AS total
FROM sales_data
GROUP BY ROLLUP(region, product);
```

💡 **`GROUPING_ID(cols…)`** packs multiple `GROUPING()` bits into a single integer (bitmask). Useful for `ORDER BY` to keep totals at the bottom, or for assigning a report-level label:
```sql
ORDER BY GROUPING_ID(region, product), region, product
-- 0 = detail, 1 = product-subtotal, 2 = region-subtotal, 3 = grand total
```

<div class="quiz" data-quiz-id="q-rollup-vs-cube">
  <div class="quiz-kind">Scenario</div>
  <div class="quiz-q">You need sales totals: by (region, product), by region subtotal, and the grand total — but NOT by product alone. Which operator fits best?</div>
  <ol class="quiz-opts">
    <li><code>GROUP BY CUBE(region, product)</code></li>
    <li data-correct><code>GROUP BY ROLLUP(region, product)</code></li>
    <li><code>GROUP BY GROUPING SETS ((region, product), (product), ())</code></li>
    <li>Plain <code>GROUP BY region, product</code></li>
  </ol>
  <div class="quiz-why"><code>ROLLUP</code> produces the hierarchical prefix subtotals: <code>(region, product)</code>, <code>(region)</code>, <code>()</code>. <code>CUBE</code> would also add the <code>(product)</code> grouping you don't want. Use <code>GROUPING SETS</code> when the combinations aren't a clean prefix hierarchy.</div>
</div>

